The ServiceNow/DocuSign integration allows you to directly send DocuSign template envelopes directly from Task records, all while viewing real-time updates to the completion status of the document within the task.

 

Pre-requisites:

  1. A DocuSign account is required.
    1. This can be a Developer (Sandbox) account for demo/testing purposes. To set up a Developer account, click here and follow the instructions.
  2. A DocuSign template is required.
    1. These are created within DocuSign and synced with the app. For template information, click here. 

 

How does it work?

The DocuSign integraiton uses ServiceNow REST Messages to initiate communication to DocuSign's API. When a document is sent for signature from a Task, the DocuSign integration invokes a REST Message that authenticates with DocuSign and creates the envelope for signature. At the same time, an envelope log is created in Envelopes table. The task is updated with a link back to the DocuSign document, and the user is notified from DocuSign.

When the document is signed, DocuSign calls a custom Connect function that initiates a call back to ServiceNow's REST API to let ServiceNow know that the document has been signed. When this happens, the task is updated letting know anyone viewing the task that the signature has been received.

Finally, both templates and Connect (webhook) configurations are synced from DocuSign into ServiceNow.

 

Setup Instructions

Within DocuSign:

** These instructions are assuming you are using a Sandbox account. Real accounts may have different instructions ** 

 First, log into DocuSign. if brought to the main interface, make sure you go to the Admin interface by clicking the icon at the top right, and clicking Go to Admin:

Once in the Admin console, navigate on the left menu to "APIs and Keys". This is how you will set up DocuSign to allow authentication from ServiceNow.

Notice you already have some API info, but we need an Integrator Key to do the authentication. Click Add Integrator Key and follow the steps to create a new Integrator Key. If you followed the steps properly, you will now have an Integrator Key.

Once the Integrator Key is created, you should now have an API Username, an API Password, an API Account ID and a new Integrator Key. If everything was set up properly you should now see this:

 Store your API credentials in a safe place!

Next, create a template. From DocuSign, go back to the non-Admin interface and navigate to Templates. Upload a new file (for example, an NDA document), give your template a name and submit your new template.

We're now ready to move onto the ServiceNow setup.

 

Within ServiceNow

After loading the update set, notice the newly-created Application Menu. Here is a quick rundown of the features in each of the modules:

  • Templates - These are DocuSign templates used when you send a task-based record for signature. These sync automatically and manually from DocuSign into SN via a scheduled job.
  • Trigger rules - if you want to trigger an automatic creation of a template when a task is inserted, this is where you can configure this behavior.
  • Envelopes - A log of all DocuSign Envelopes (documents) sent, and their associated task.
  • DocuSign Template Sync job - this job runs daily to sync DocuSign templates from DS to SN.
  • Table configurations - REQUIRED - in order to send documents from tasks, a table configuration needs to be created for that table.
  • Connect configurations - Use this to manage DocuSign Connect APIs directly from the SN platform.
  • Properties - where you enter your API info. More details later.

Remember those DocuSign API credentials from earlier? No?! You didn't write them down!? I knew it...! First, go to DocuSign and go to your API keys, and then within the ServiceNow instance go to DocuSign Integration -> Administration -> Properties. Plug in your API credentials to the properties page. You should be able to copy and paste your credentials into the corresponding fields with no problems.

After the API credentials are added, the first thing we need to do is sync your template created above into DocuSign. Do this by navigating to DocuSign Integration -> Templates. In the Template list, click the "Sync Templates from DocuSign button". This will copy templates and their info (not attachments) from DocuSign into ServiceNow. Once you sync, you should see the template you created above in the list of templates. Also this is a great way to test your API credentials. :)

** If this step fails, double check your API credentials!! **

Next, a Table Configuration must be created. Even if signer fields are not added you must have a configuration for the tables from which you would like to send documents.  

Let's create an example as if we want to be able to send documents from HR Tasks:

Table - HR Task

Signer field: "x_snc_ds_int_document_signer". string field name of the field that contains a user reference that acts as the signer.

Signer field display: "Document signer". Display in the modal that pops up in the task when you send the document.

 

 

Submit the table configuration. You can now send DocuSign templates from an HR Task.

Finally, we need to configure a Connect configuration. This allows DocuSign to call ServiceNow's REST API when events are triggered, such as Document Signed. If you want a two-way integration this is how it's set up.

 Navigate to DocuSign Integration -> Administration -> Table configurations. If you already have a table configuration here then you're almost ready to go! If not, one will need to be created. Fill out the following fields in the Connect configuration:

Name: ServiceNow - Document Signed
Active: checked
REST Endpoint: Document Signed
Enable log: checked
Trigger events -> Envelope fields: checked
Trigger events -> Envelope Signed: checked
Sign with X509 Cert: checked

Submit. Go back to the record and click the "Publish to DocuSign Connect APIs" link at the bottom of the page. This will create the API within DocuSign!

Giving it a test

Since our table configuration is on HR Task, navigate to an HR Task record. In the HR Task, configure the form to show the "Document signer" field. Fill in the Document Signer with a user from the User table. This user must have a valid email address as DocuSign sends signature requests to an email address! Using a user without an email address will cause the integration to fail. 

From the HR task, click the "Send for Signature" UI action. This opens up a Modal dialog to fill out with information about the recipient and the template to use.

For Template, choose the template you synced.

You can choose to send the document to recipients from the HR Task record. This field is configurable and pulls from your Table Configuration. If you check the box for Document Signer, the sys_user in this field will receive a signature request.

If you are doing this for a demo, make sure you use a user that has an email that you can control (for example, your ServiceNow email) so you can log in and show the DocuSign email.

When adding "Other users", you must make sure you click "Add" when you find a user from the reference field. 

The Subject is the subject of the email the user will receive. 

Click Send. If you forgot to add a template or users, a form validation will pop up an alert to make sure to complete the form. Otherwise, a success alert will pop up letting you know the document was sent properly!

 If everything is successfully configured, you will see the following in the activity log:

 When the Document is signed in DocuSign, the activity of this task will be updated to record when the document was signed and by whom.
